knowledge_graph.title: Castanea crenata
knowledge_graph.description: Castanea crenata, the Japanese chestnut or Korean chestnut, is a species of chestnut native to Japan and Korea. Castanea crenata exhibits resistance to Phytophthora cinnamomi, the fungal pathogen that causes ink disease in several Castanea species.

related_questions.question: Are Japanese chestnuts edible?
related_questions.snippet: Japanese chestnuts are a popular autumn food. They are known as “kuri” in Japanese and “marron” in French, especially when used in Western-style desserts. As autumn approaches in Japan, the hearty chestnut comes into season. The chestnut is only available in the fall and winter.

related_questions.question: What is the difference between American and Japanese chestnut?
related_questions.snippet: The Japanese chestnut has narrow leaves, smaller than either American chestnut or sweet chestnut, with small, sharply-pointed teeth and many hairs on the underside of the leaf and is the most blight-resistant species.

related_questions.question: What is a chestnut called in Japanese?
related_questions.snippet: Chestnuts / kuri (くり in Japanese) are nuts that grow on chestnut trees in Japan from September to October. They are popular for their fluffy texture, sweet taste, and golden appearance.

related_questions.question: How big do Japanese chestnut trees get?
related_questions.snippet: description. The Japanese chestnut (C. crenata), a similar shrub or tree that may grow to 9 metres (30 feet) or more, is found at elevations of less than 915 metres (3,000 feet); it has heart-shaped leaves about 17 cm (7 inches) long.
